Demotivating people is hard. Demotivating developers is harder. Every single developer starts a project with a lot of passion. There are these question that lay in the foundation of each project:

What architecture to use? What technologies to use? Do we need database? What is the MVP looking like? Will it include a lot of animations? Will there be login and login with social providers as Facebook, Google etc? Do we store sensitive data? How and where to store it?What navigation framework to use? Any many many more on the list.

I cannot imagine that there is a developer out there who started a brand new project without even the smallest bit of passion. But as you know, things change in time and a lot of projects fail, a lot of people leave and even projects which started with a bright future, end up in a dead end street. Sometimes, when you are not careful at your interview and you forget to ask the right questions, you end up in a project which might not be the best place to join right now.

Here is my list of the most demotivating stuff which lead sooner or later a project to its way to hell. These are indicators that should warn you that you may not get the best benefit of staying in such projects. After all, we all want to learn and share our learnings and not having an opportunity to do so can lead us to a project where we are just waiting for the time at work to pass just to go home.

## Demotivation list

### There are no tests. There is no plan for tests.

### PR reviews just pass without a single comment from team members.

### You only do features. No bugs, no refactoring

### Doing features requires you to contact at least 3 other persons

### Features never contain all you need. You have to gather it yourself

### Backlog stays full of tasks for days and weeks

### You don't have conventions nor do you follow any. Business logic is everywhere. And everyone stays silent about it.

### Product people says that there is no time for refactoring. We need to increase our market.

### No QA person present. Do the release testing yourself.

### The team lead just doesn't care. So does the product owner. Who actually cares?

### The CTO of the company never finds time to talk to your team. Neither to understand what your project does. Nor to know whether you have tests or not.

### A lot of people say they don't believe in the project but they stay for the show
